<section class="hero">
  <h1>Lump Sum or <em>Ladder In?</em></h1>
  <div class="hero-subtitle">Two ways to put money into Bitcoin &mdash; and which one served you better depended on where price sat in the Power Law channel. And a third question the binary hides: when the channel is stretched, whether to deploy high at all.</div>
</section>

<main class="content-area">

  {% include 'components/tool-framing.njk' %}

  <div class="section-intro lsl-prose">
    <p>Accumulating Bitcoin can involve both a lump sum and DCA. This page examines how the two compared historically, and how that comparison shifts with where price sits in its Power Law channel. The next, sister page &mdash; Your Bitcoin Deployment Plan &mdash; then provides a calculator to help you get comfortable with your own decision.</p>
    <p class="lsl-footnote"><strong>DCA</strong> &mdash; dollar-cost averaging: deploying a fixed amount on a regular cadence (e.g. every paycheck) as a savings discipline, rather than all at once.</p>
    <p>Looking back at Bitcoin&rsquo;s price history, the rule of thumb is that a lump-sum buy has, on average, outperformed spreading smaller buys out over time. Generally, Bitcoin price trends up over time, and time in the market beats waiting on the sidelines.</p>
    <p>But that average hides something useful. The lump-sum vs. ladder choice is not so much about timing, price or market sentiment but really about <em>where bitcoin&rsquo;s price is in the Power Law channel</em>. Low in the channel, you&rsquo;re effectively buying at a <em>discount</em> to trend: if you hold the Power Law thesis, price tends to revert upward over time, so deploying decisively captured more Bitcoin. Higher in the channel, the gap between lump-sum and laddering narrowed, and laddering more often came out ahead. <span class="lsl-aside">(Why that edge is weaker than it looks &mdash; and what it means for your own deployment &mdash; is the subject of Your Bitcoin Deployment Plan.)</span></p>
    <p>And underneath all of it: historically, <em>over a long enough horizon</em>, every entry &mdash; even the literal worst tops in Bitcoin&rsquo;s history &mdash; has recovered to a large multiple. What this page explores is tactics, but commitment is the foundation.</p>
  </div>

