      </table>
    </div>
    <div class="lsl-takeaway" id="lslBackstopTakeaway"></div>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════ SUPPORTING: volatility compression ════════ -->
  <section class="lsl-section">
    <p class="lsl-secondary-label">Supporting &middot; why the tactic matters less over time</p>
    <h2>The upper channel is compressing</h2>
    <div class="lsl-prose">
      <p>Being high in the channel is better read as a <em>risk</em> than an opportunity &mdash; it&rsquo;s where a lump buys into the mean-reversion the channel predicts. And those spikes high into the channel have grown smaller and less frequent cycle over cycle, so the chance of being caught deploying high is diminishing. Maximum channel position reached, by four-year window:</p>
    </div>
    <div class="lsl-table-wrap">
      <table class="lsl-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Window</th><th>Max channel position</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody id="lslCompressionBody"></tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <div class="lsl-prose">
      <p>As Bitcoin matures it increasingly lives low-to-mid channel, where decisiveness has paid off &mdash; consistent with the volatility compression on <a href="/the-doubling-ladder">The Doubling Ladder</a> and the Power Law&rsquo;s shrinking cycle peaks. The channel increasingly just says <em>commit</em>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

