  <!-- ════════ HONESTY LAYER ════════ -->
  <section class="lsl-section">
    <div class="belief-context">
      <div class="belief-context-label">A note on prerequisite reading</div>
      <p><strong>This page uses the Power Law channel to frame the decision.</strong> If that model isn&rsquo;t useful to you, neither is this page. <a href="/the-power-law#channel">The Channel</a> lays out the bands, the evidence, and the attribution &mdash; read it first if the frame is new.</p>
    </div>

    <h3>Where this doesn&rsquo;t apply to you</h3>
    <div class="lsl-caveats">
      <div class="lsl-caveat">
        <h4>The Power Law is empirical, not guaranteed.</h4>
        <p>It&rsquo;s an observation that has held across roughly fifteen years &mdash; not a promise. Price has stayed above the 0.42&times; floor about <strong>97% of the time</strong>, but future cycles aren&rsquo;t assured, and every reading here assumes the channel&rsquo;s shape keeps holding.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="lsl-caveat">
        <h4>Hindsight flatters the fit.</h4>
        <p>The bands were drawn through the data &mdash; the trend fits the record with about <strong>96% R&sup2;</strong> &mdash; which makes &ldquo;buy low in the channel&rdquo; look prescient. But that is an <em>in-sample fit, not a prediction</em>: this is what <em>would have</em> happened; the past isn&rsquo;t promised to the next buyer.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="lsl-caveat">
        <h4>This is an exploration, not advice for your specific situation.</h4>
        <p>It compares two tactics across history to make a point. What to actually do with your own money &mdash; and looking forward, not just back &mdash; is the <a href="/your-deployment-plan">next page</a>&rsquo;s job, with its own cautions.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <ul class="negative-space-list">
      <li><strong>Not a price target.</strong> The page never tells you where price is going &mdash; only how the deployment comparison shifted with where price <em>was</em> in the channel.</li>
      <li><strong>Not a trading strategy.</strong> The only thing being compared is deployment decisiveness by position in the channel. Getting in, not trading in and out.</li>
      <li><strong>Not a timing signal.</strong> &ldquo;Decisive&rdquo; and &ldquo;spread&rdquo; are about position in the channel, not a prediction that a move is imminent.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════ METHODOLOGY ════════ -->
  <div class="lsl-attribution">
    <span class="lsl-attribution-label">Channel framework &amp; coefficients</span>
    The Power Law channel &mdash; floor at 0.42&times; trend, upper band at 3&times; trend &mdash; was developed by <a href="https://www.porkopolis.io/thechart/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Matthew Me&zcaron;inskis</strong></a> at Porkopolis Economics. Coefficients used: <code>a = 1.6&times;10<sup>&minus;17</sup></code>, <code>b = 5.77</code>. See <a href="/the-power-law#channel">The Channel</a> for the full case and attribution.
  </div>

  <div class="lsl-method">
    <div class="lsl-method-label">Methodology</div>
    <ul>
      <li>Channel position is the log-space location between floor and ceiling: <code>(ln(price/trend) &minus; ln 0.42) / (ln 3.0 &minus; ln 0.42)</code> &mdash; 0 at the floor, 1 at the upper band.</li>
      <li>Backtest: a fixed sum deployed all-at-once vs. laddered equally across the chosen window, comparing BTC accumulated, bucketed by entry channel position. The advantage is amount-invariant.</li>
      <li>Commitment backstop: <strong>today-anchored</strong>. For each hold length N, entries deployed ~N years ago (a ~1.8-year window centred N years before today) are bucketed by channel position and valued at <strong>today&rsquo;s live price &divide; entry price</strong> &mdash; what each entry would be worth now, not its value at some historical cycle peak. Recomputes live as the price moves.</li>
      <li id="lslMethodWindow"></li>
      <li>Today&rsquo;s channel position is computed at load from the latest sample and the live spot (CoinGecko, via the shared fetch) &mdash; never baked in.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

